title: Encyclopaedia of Indian President Part 2 | StudyIQ Podcast Episode 33 for GS Paper 2 UPSC | StudyIQ
description:
Hello students, welcome to StudyIQ's new initiative: "The Podcast". The podcast will help you in unwinding your UPSC journey by enhancing your revision of UPSC preparation. The goal of "The Podcast" is to help you in revising your entire syllabus of UPSC with macro and micro topic analysis. For your convenience, we will cover all the concepts which become important for your UPSC prelims and Mains examination.

The biggest advantage of "The Podcast" is that it will follow the sequence which is defined by the UPSC. We will cover all GS papers with major topics and sub-topics. The structure of the podcast will be lucid as it will define the topic, then it will cover concepts, then it will discuss the dimensions important for mains answer writing and in the last we will conclude the topic.

You can listen to this podcast via multiple platforms like YouTube, Spotify, Google Podcast, kuku fm, Hubhopper and Apple Podcast.

title: How to SPEAK with CONFIDENCE in PUBLIC Step by Step? How to Overcome Stage Fear? Public Speaking Art
description:
‡§≠‡•Ä‡§°‡§º ‡§ï‡•á ‡§∏‡§æ‡§Æ‡§®‡•á ‡§¨‡•ã‡§≤‡§®‡•á ‡§ï‡§æ ‡§°‡§∞ ‡§ï‡•à‡§∏‡•á ‡§ñ‡§§‡§Æ ‡§ï‡§∞‡•á‡§Ç? ‡§ï‡§ø‡§§‡§®‡•á ‡§π‡•Ä ‡§≤‡•ã‡§ó‡•ã‡§Ç ‡§ï‡•á ‡§∏‡§æ‡§Æ‡§®‡•á CONFIDENCE ‡§∏‡•á ‡§¨‡•ã‡§≤ ‡§ï‡§∞ ‡§≤‡•ã‡§ó‡•ã‡§Ç ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Ö‡§™‡§®‡•Ä ‡§¨‡§æ‡§§‡•ã‡§Ç ‡§∏‡•á ‡§ï‡•à‡§∏‡•á ‡§ú‡•Ä‡§§‡•á‡§Ç? How to Handle Stage Fear with High Self Confidence? How to become an Impressive Public Speaker and Boost your Confidence? This video will give you free and easy methods, step by step, on the art of impressive public speaking!

Many students and people who want to get success in their business, buy paid course or online classes for public speaking aur effective communication skills, but this video will give you very simple and free step by step methods to become a better public speaker. This video is very helpful for all beginners or intermediate or professional public speakers.

An impressive stage speaking confidence is crucial when addressing a large audience for several reasons. Firstly, it helps to engage the audience, capturing their attention and maintaining their interest throughout the presentation. Secondly, confidence establishes the speaker's credibility, making them appear knowledgeable and trustworthy, which in turn makes the audience more receptive to the message being conveyed.

Confidence also plays a role in effective communication, ensuring that the speaker's thoughts are articulated clearly and accurately. It can reduce the speaker's anxiety and nervousness, allowing for a more enjoyable and successful speaking experience. Additionally, a confident speaker is more persuasive, conveying passion and conviction that makes their arguments compelling.

Moreover, confidence demonstrates professionalism, essential in business and academic settings. It creates a positive impression, showing the speaker as polished and prepared. Finally, confident speakers are better equipped to manage challenging situations, addressing difficulties calmly and competently. In summary, impressive stage speaking confidence is vital for audience engagement, credibility, effective communication, and professionalism while speaking in front of many people.

title: LISTEN TO THIS DAILY NIGHT Before You Sleep: Affirmations Positive Thinking, Health, Success, Money
description:
How will it work? Affirmations work because our brain is like a super computer that listens to what we say and think. When we say positive things to ourselves, our brain starts to believe them, and that can make us feel happier and more confident.

Think of your brain as a garden, and your thoughts as seeds. When you plant positive seeds by saying nice things to yourself, they grow into beautiful flowers. But if you plant negative seeds, they grow into weeds that can take over the garden. Affirmations help us grow more flowers and fewer weeds, making our brain garden a beautiful and happy place to be.

These Every Night Affirmations are so powerful that you can change your mindset, thought system and you can achieve everything in your life. These affirmations are to be listened daily for better power!

Affirmations are like magic words we say to ourselves to feel good and strong. They are like a kind friend who always says nice things to make us believe in ourselves. When we say these magic words, we can do amazing things! So, whenever you feel sad or scared, say something nice to yourself, like "I am brave" or "I can do it!" and you'll feel much better. Remember, saying kind things to yourself is a superpower!

description:
Uncovering the Mysterious Science of Dreaming | Letstuteüß†

#dream #sciencecuriosity  #uncovering 

Have you ever woken up from a dream and wondered, "What was that all about?" Dreams can be mysterious, confusing, and sometimes downright bizarre. But have you ever stopped to wonder why we get these random dreams in the first place? In this video, we'll explore the science behind dreaming and why our brains conjure up these strange and often surreal experiences.

We'll start by looking at the different stages of sleep and how they affect our dreams. Did you know that we dream during the REM (Rapid Eye Movement) stage of sleep? We'll explain what happens during this stage and why it's so important for our overall health and well-being.

Next, we'll dive into the different theories about why we dream. From Freud's psychoanalytic theory to more modern interpretations, we'll explore the different ideas about why our brains create these strange and often nonsensical experiences.

But what about those really weird dreams that seem to come out of nowhere? We'll talk about the role of our subconscious mind in dreaming and how our deepest fears, desires, and memories can influence the content of our dreams.

Finally, we'll offer some tips for interpreting your dreams and making sense of the messages your brain may be trying to send you. Whether you're a frequent dreamer or just curious about the science behind sleep, this video is sure to offer some fascinating insights into the mysterious world of dreaming.

title: Why Autism Is Often Missed in Women and Girls | Kate Kahle | TED
description:
Women and girls with autism spectrum disorder often don't display the behaviors people typically associate with neurodivergence, greatly impacting when, how -- and if -- they are diagnosed. Autism acceptance advocate Kate Kahle makes the case for more research into this gender discrepancy, sharing her personal experience with masking, being diagnosed as a teenager and how it allowed her to better understand herself. "Autism is not a disease, and it doesn't need to be cured," she says. "It's just a different way some brains can work."

title: Huawei Nova 10 Pro Hands-on | The Ultimate TikTok Phone?
description:
‚ÄúA phone for the TikTok generation.‚Äù
That‚Äôs what I heard when I was at IFA last week getting some early hands-on time with the newly announced Huawei Nova 10 and 10 pro. 

The Huawei Nova 10 is 6.67-inches in the hand. It has a 2652x1200 resolution display, with a dynamic 120hz refresh rate; meaning it can scale its frame rate depending on what you're doing, to save battery.

The 10 Pro has the same display specs although it‚Äôs slightly bigger at 6.78 inches. 
All of this display tech is coupled with dual stereo speakers on both phones, making for a decent viewing and gaming experience.

A mid-range Snapdragon 778G chipset powers both phones, with 8GB of RAM, and 256GB of storage in tow. 

The phones have slightly different batteries, with the Nova 10 packing a 4000mAh battery and the pro boasting a 4500mAh cell.
 
Neither phone supports wireless charging, however, the pro does support impressive 100 watt fast charging, while the normal nova 10 is limited to a still impressive 66 watt huawei fast charging. And you do get a charger in the box, so bonus points for Huawei there.

Both devices feature a 60MP Ultra-Wide Angle front facing camera, capable of 4K video capture, and the HUAWEI nova 10 Pro also features an additional 8MP portrait camera for better selfie snapping. 

Long gone are the days when having the biggest megapixel count on your phone meant that you had the best camera phone on the market. Software, AI and post image processing all play into the quietly of your smartphone camera from both a user experience point of view and producing a plastering image.

Samsung is leading the way with foldable phones right now, with the brand new Galaxy Z Fold 4 and Galaxy Z Flip 4 setting the standard for other phone makers to follow ‚Äì and the next in line to launch a foldable handset or two could well be Oppo.

title: There's never been a worse time to buy an Oculus Quest 2...
description:
Recently, my partner and I met up with some friends to enjoy a summer barbeque ‚Äì making the most of the good weather while we could. But, as is often the case in the UK, it wasn‚Äôt long before the sun hid behind the clouds and our outdoor party was rained off. 

Looking for a way to keep everyone entertained, our host pulled out their parents' Oculus Quest 2 and we took turns to crush Beat Saber tracks and earn high scores in Resident Evil 4 VR‚Äôs The Mercenaries mode. The people who didn't regularly use VR seemed impressed with what the headset could do and were keen to pick up one for themselves.

Knowing that I regularly write about and use this kind of tech, a couple of them reached out to me to ask about the best VR headsets to go for ‚Äì with a particular interest in the Quest 2 they had enjoyed using at the barbeque.

title: Next Xbox Game Pass Ultimate upgrade will make your gaming PC redundant...
description:
Xbox Game Pass members might soon be able to stream games that aren‚Äôt included in the subscription service, as Microsoft expands the functionality of Xbox Cloud Gaming.

Bundled with all Xbox Game Pass Ultimate subscriptions, Xbox Cloud Gaming lets you stream titles to your Xbox Series X|S, Xbox One, and PC. Currently, you can only stream select titles from the Xbox Game Pass library. At Microsoft's 2019 X019 event, the company shared plans to let members "stream from the cloud Xbox games that they already own or will purchase" by 2020.¬†

That window came and went without the update, but Microsoft reaffirmed that goal this year in a June Xbox Wire post(opens in new tab), with editor Will Tuttle saying we could expect it "later this year." Now, it appears that the feature could be rolling out sooner rather than later.

Read more - https://www.techradar.com/news/next-xbox-game-pass-ultimate-upgrade-will-make-your-gaming-pc-redundant
(Image credit: Microsoft)

title: You could soon be seeing a lot more ads on your iPhone...
description:
As we wait patiently for the iPhone 14 to show up, a new report suggests some significant changes could be coming to the software on iPhones and iPads: specifically‚Ä¶ more advertising‚Ä¶ in Apple's‚Ä¶ own‚Ä¶ apps.

This comes via the reliable Apple-focused journalist Mark Gurman at Bloomberg, who says that Apple is keen on expanding its integrated advertising efforts. A number of ads already show up in the News and Stocks apps, as well as the App Store.

And now Gurman is suggesting that those apps could eventually be joined by Apple Maps, as well as the Apple Podcasts and the Apple Books apps. 

We might also see an expansion into Apple TV Plus content with adverts already starting to appear in the platform's Friday Night Baseball coverage, for example.
Read more - https://www.techradar.com/news/you-could-soon-be-seeing-a-lot-more-ads-on-your-iphone

title: The Fix For a "Boring Life" - Sei Shonagen - The Pillow Book
description:
It feels natural, at times, to lament how boring our lives are. We do the same things each week, nothing special or exciting ever seems to happen. We enviously compare our dull routines to the adventures of others. An antidote to our sense of tedium can be found a thousand years ago in the work of Sei Shonagon, a lady-in-waiting at the Imperial Place in Kyoto.

‚ÄúIt feels natural, at times, to lament how boring our lives are. We do the same sorts of things each week, nothing special or exciting ever seems to happen. We enviously compare our dull routines to the adventures of others.  
 An antidote to our sense of tedium can be found in the work of Sei Shonagon. Around a thousand years ago, she kept a journal of the decade or so she spent as a lady-in-waiting at the Imperial Place in Kyoto, then the capital of Japan. Despise the high-status of her job, her daily life was, externally, deeply uneventful: an afternoon‚Äôs carriage ride outside the walls of the court compound might be the highlight of a year; a day trip to hear a sermon in a temple seems to have been the farthest extent of her travels; she spent all most all of her time indoors, in just two or three rooms; she saw the same few people month after month; her work largely involved keeping respectfully silent, knowing when to bow and remembering the complex titles of various officials‚Ä¶‚Äù

‚ÄúOne of the more consistently confronting and at times embarrassing concepts that psychology forces us to consider is that of an ‚Äòinner child.‚Äô All of us have along the years made such efforts to become adults, it can be at once grating and dispiriting to be told that there might, nevertheless, be an ‚Äòinner child‚Äô still lodged somewhere within us.
But in truth, we contain within ourselves a version of all the people we have ever been. There is, in recessive form, somewhere in the folds of our natures, a confused teenager, a sad child, a jealous or hungry infant. No version of us entirely disappears, it is merely added to and buttressed, just like an oak tree that still contains, in its rings, the marks of all its former circumferences‚Ä¶‚Äù

title: Why Successful Love Requires Vulnerability
description:
We can state the matter starkly: we cannot be good lovers if we don‚Äôt know how to be vulnerable. 
Sign up to our mailing list to receive 10% off your first order with us: https://r1.dotdigital-pages.com/p/6TU0-63X/hellotsol

You can read more on this and other subjects on our blog, here: https://bit.ly/3ZviHhi

‚ÄúWe can state the matter starkly: we cannot be good lovers if we don‚Äôt know how to be vulnerable. 

We make ourselves psychologically vulnerable whenever we let a partner know some of the ways in which we are weak, needy, scared, immature, incompetent or just plain odd - that is, some of the ways in which we are human. To be vulnerable is to dare to take off the usual cloak of normality and sensibleness with which we navigate the world and for once, to show someone who we really are, with all the fragility and unusualness implied. We might, as vulnerable people, admit to a desire to be mummied or daddied, to curl into a ball, to cry over a so-called small thing, to be reassured about an apparently minor flaw, to call up our lover every ten minutes, to suffer from anxiety or paranoia, to speak in a regressive voice or to hug a favourite stuffed animal‚Ä¶‚Äù

‚ÄúAlmost inevitably, somewhere along the path of our friendships, we are fated to stumble upon one of the most paradoxical yet universal of characters: the envious friend.

At one level, this person is kind, sympathises with us in our sorrows and believes that they want the best for us. Yet, despite such salutary affections, we may not be able to overlook some more troubling dynamics shimmering beneath the surface:
- when we invite them for dinner, they repeatedly ‚Äòforget‚Äô to say thank you.
- when we have a new partner, they don't appear overly pleased
- when we get a new job, they don‚Äôt ask us a single question about how its going.

The situation is as wounding as it is uncharted. How are we to cope? Can this be happening to us? A few ways forward suggest themselves‚Ä¶‚Äù

‚ÄúIn mid-September 1888, a penniless Dutchman, who would in a few months be committed to an asylum and be dead within two years, sat down in the eastern corner of the Place du Forum in Arles and set to work on one of the most astonishing and beloved paintings ever made. ‚ÄòCaf√© Terrace at Night‚Äô juxtaposes our snug night time rituals under our defiant man-made lamps with the ultimate mysteries and sublimity of the cosmos.

And yet, as we know, Van Gogh found no buyers for his masterpiece; no museum came begging, no gallery gave a damn. His work appeared wholly worthless to his entire era. He could barely afford lunch or a new pair of shoes. The local children mocked him. Rarely has a more despised or marginal figure walked the earth‚Ä¶‚Äù

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs an enormous privilege to have an adolescence - and, to an extent rarely spoken about, not everyone gets the chance to have one. Adolescence isn‚Äôt just a particular time of one‚Äôs second decade, and it won‚Äôt unfold automatically simply when one reaches fourteen or seventeen and three quarters.
 Adolescence properly understood is a state in which we‚Äôre able to explore - with courage and newfound independence - who we might be outside of the projections and mental dictates placed upon us with enormous ingenuity and great force by our parents.
 Parents are the greatest propagandists that any of us will ever meet with - and part of their genius is that we rarely know what they are up to. Below the surface they are engaged in a ruthless and ongoing attempt to sell us a version of reality: to tell us what we are ‚Äòreally‚Äô like, what we actually need, what life is truly about - and who they have been and what their motives are. It goes without saying that some of their ideas will be eminently correct but the function of adolescence is to take a good long look at, and deal with, the ones that aren‚Äôt‚Ä¶‚Äù

title: Every Society Collapses, Here‚Äôs How to Survive...
description:
The news is often determined to tell us that we live in uniquely critical times, beset by political disasters and afflicted by terrible crises and that the demise of human civilisation is surely imminent. We are encouraged to view the world - and our own lives - in bleak, apocalyptic terms. Oddly, history can be powerfully consoling, not because it tells us that our times are great, but because it shows us how normal large societal troubles really are.

‚ÄúThe news is often determined to tell us that we live in uniquely critical times, beset by political disasters and afflicted by terrible crises and that the demise of human civilisation is surely imminent. We are encouraged to view the world - and our own lives - in bleak, apocalyptic terms. Oddly, history can be powerfully consoling, not because it tells us that our times are great, but because it shows us how normal large societal troubles really are. 
The English 18th century historian Edward Gibbon is particularly helpful with this task of bringing us to a less frightened perspective. His massive, elegantly written work covers 1500 years, from the pinnacle of Roman power around the year 180 AD, through the collapse of the Western Empire to the final fall of its last outpost, the city of Constantinople, in 1453.  Gibbon started work on the series of volumes  around 1770 and completed the final volume on a summer‚Äôs evening in 1787 while he was on holiday in Switzerland‚Ä¶‚Äù

description:

One of the strangest and saddest phenomena of psychological life is that there are parents, too many parents, who end up - while sometimes only half realising it - bullying their own children.  The bullying may take many forms. Why do parents bully their children?

‚ÄúOne of the strangest and saddest phenomena of psychological life is that there are parents, too many parents, who end up - while sometimes only half realising it - bullying their own children.
The bullying may take many forms. Why do parents bully their children? In short, in order to try to feel better about themselves. Because they suffer intensely in the very same area that they are bullying their child in. If we, as children, want to know what our parents were afraid of or haunted by, we only need to ask: in what areas did they bully me? What did they make me feel scared or inadequate about? Someone made them feel awful and they surmise - by twisted logic - that they will feel better through the process of making their own child feel very bad indeed; they aren‚Äôt doing it personally, the child is collateral damage to a misguided project of healing and attenuation of symptoms. It doesn‚Äôt make any sense of course,  but it may actually work for the parent, for a time.‚Äù

title: NCERT Textbook Revision: Why It Happens Every Few Years | Audio Article | Drishti IAS
description:
Recently NCERT books have come at the center of political controversy. This controversy has arisen mainly for two reasons. The first reason in this is the Covid epidemic and the second is the National Education Policy, 2020. In fact, the closure of schools due to the Covid epidemic caused great damage to learning outcomes. The annual session lagged behind. In view of this, various education boards and parents requested NCERT to reduce the load of syllabus. Significantly, such a suggestion was given long ago by the Yashpal Committee in 1992 itself. The recommendations of this committee are called 'learning without burden'. The Yashpal Committee, back in 2009 reiterated this recommendation that the syllabus should be reduced. That's why in this article an attempt has been made to find out when and what controversies have been there on NCERT books. Along with this, an attempt has also been made to understand what the latest controversy over NCERT books is. An attempt has been made to find answers to other such questions in this article.

title: Olympics Games: story of the modern Olympics - IN FOCUS | UPSC Current affairs | Drishti IAS
description:
On April 6, 1896, the inaugural Olympic Games kicked off in Athens, Greece. Harkening back to the mythologised Olympic games from ancient Greece, the Games were an overwhelming success, paving the way for modern sports competition as we know it. However, most people know little about the genesis of the modern Games beyond the fact that it was the brainchild of French Baron Pierre de Coubertin.

title: Map Revision Series: Ep-06| NEWS ON MAP | UPSC P.T. - 2023| DRISHTI IAS
description:
Dear Viewers,
Team Drishti feels glad to announce that we have again started a ‚ÄòMap Revision Series‚Äô in place of regular #NewsOnMap Programme. We have tried our best to present you with a compilation of important #placesinnews throughout last year. We believe it will help you much to boost your knowledge towards this subject. In this way, it will hopefully strengthen you during IAS PT 2023 to be held on 28th May.

This episode covers important news from November, 2022. You should also go through News on Map weekly episodes of November, 2022.

title: Prelims Revision Series 2023 - Art and Culture - 01 | UPSC Revision | Drishti IAS
description:
Dear Viewers, Team Drishti IAS Hindi feels glad to announce that we have started this UPSC PT Current Affairs Revision Series 2023 based on Art and Culture. We have tried our best to present you a compilation of important events that occurred in the field of Science And Technology throughout the year. We believe it helps you much to boost your knowledge towards this subject. In this way, it will hopefully strengthen you during IAS PT 2023 (Prelims 2023). Other programs related to PT 2023 are also available on this channel.

title: Explained: Could the Renminbi Challenge the Dollar? I Drishti IAS
description:
The rising influence of China‚Äôs currency yuan has prompted questions about whether it can oust the US dollar as the world‚Äôs dominant currency. 

As per a Bloomberg report on Tuesday (4 April), the yuan has replaced the US dollar as the most traded currency in Russia. 

Let‚Äôs take a closer look at the rise of the Chinese currency globally and if it can overthrow the US dollar. According to Bloomberg, the yuan put the dollar behind in monthly trading volume this February in Russia, increasing further in March.

Why RBI Keeps Repo Rate Unchanged at 6.5% | IN NEWS | Drishti IAS


The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has announced its decision to keep the repo rate unchanged at 6.5% in this latest business news update. This development comes as a relief for homebuyers who have been grappling with the impact of higher loan costs. As the central bank's repo rate decision has far-reaching implications for the economy and businesses, this video provides an in-depth analysis of the reasons behind the RBI's decision and its potential impact on the real estate market.

description:
Team Drishti IAS has brought in-depth comprehensive analysis of UPSC prelims previous year questions. In this program, we will go through multiple question types, provide tips and strategies for success as well as share insider knowledge that will help you ace the upcoming UPSC exams. In this series we will cover all subject wise previous year questions paper like History, Economy, Geography, Polity, Environment & Ecology, Science & Technology etc. It will be our endeavor to make you feel confident to qualify your upcoming exam through this series.

title: Science & Technology: Comprehensive Analysis of Previous Year Questions 2021 ‡•§ Drishti IAS
description:
Team Drishti IAS has brought in-depth comprehensive analysis of UPSC prelims previous year questions. In this program, we will go through multiple question types, provide tips and strategies for success as well as share insider knowledge that will help you ace the upcoming UPSC exams. In this series we will cover all subject wise previous year questions paper like History, Economy, Geography, Polity, Environment & Ecology, Science & Technology etc. It will be our endeavor to make you feel confident to qualify your upcoming exam through this series.

Dear Viewer, Team Drishti is presenting a new initiative in a Quiz format. In this program we will cover questions related to the last week important news by which you will be able to assess your preparation by revising the exam oriented (UPSC, PCS etc.) news of the last one week. title: Inside the flop that changed Apple forever
description:
Apple‚Äôs Macintosh, released in 1984, is celebrated for ushering in a new era of user-friendly computing. But! The Mac owes a lot to its lesser-known, older sister Lisa. Here‚Äôs how the Lisa, while seen as a flop today, used clever interface design to welcome everyone into the personal computer era. Though as new technologies like AR, VR, and AI chatbots arrive, are we finally leaving Lisa‚Äôs legacy behind? #Apple #Technology #History
